  "excerpt": "Ahead of the holidays, here’s a quick tip on how to avoid email overload and easily keep track of gifts and packages in the mail.",
  "siteName": "Google",
  "favicon": "https://blog.google/static/blogv2/images/apple-touch-icon.png?version=pr20241113-1756",
  "text": "Dec 02, 2024 [[read-time]] min read Take the guesswork out of your deliveries. General summary You can easily track your holiday packages right in Gmail. Just click \"Allow\" on the summary card that appears at the top of your emails. If you haven't received a summary card yet, you can opt in to package tracking in your Gmail settings. Summaries were generated by Google AI. Generative AI is experimental. It’s no secret that the most wonderful time of the year can also be the busiest. From organizing schedules and travel plans to finding the perfect gift, the holidays can clutter even the most organized inboxes. That’s why this season we’re highlighting features to help you simplify the holiday swirl — including this tip on how to avoid email overload and easily keep track of gifts and packages in the mail.Whether you enable package tracking from your new summary cards or want to opt-in before your packages are on their way, we’ll show you how right from your Gmail account.Track your holiday packages with one click using summary cardsFor years, summary cards in Gmail have put key details about things like events, bills and travel updates right at the top of your emails. Our latest update is tailored for the giving (and shipping) season, offering real-time updates on your holiday purchases and a button to quickly opt in to package tracking — which brings the latest shipment information from most major U.S. shipping carriers right into Gmail — with one click.To opt in, just click “Allow” on the bottom of the summary card. Purchase summary cards are interactive and allow you to opt in to package tracking and view the status of an order. The image on the left shows the opt in button; on the right displays what people will see after package tracking is activated when receiving a package from a supported carrier. We first launched package tracking features in Gmail in 2022, and the updated summary cards make it even simpler to opt in directly from your emails.Opt in to package tracking in your Gmail settingsPackage tracking uses your tracking numbers to automatically follow your purchases’ progress and display updates in your emails. But even if you haven’t found the perfect holiday gift, you can still get prepared for the season by opting-in to package tracking right in your Gmail settings. Here’s how to set it up from your Gmail settings:Open the Gmail mobile app on your phone, and tap on the menu button (those three horizontal lines in the top left corner).Open Settings by tapping the Settings bar.In general settings (or data privacy for iOS users), you’ll find the option to opt in or turn off “Package Tracking.”You’ll only need to opt in once for package tracking, and you can opt out at any time.We hope this is helpful as the gifting season kicks off, and we’ll be sharing more tips and tools this month to help you navigate this time of year. With package tracking, you can spend less time worrying about how to intercept gifts at the door, and more time unwrapping the perfect holiday with your loved ones. Season’s greetings from Google Learn more about using Google products like Pixel, Gemini, Lens and more over the holidays. Related stories Pixel10 Google tools to use for stress-free holiday hosting By Molly McHugh-Johnson Nov 19, 2024 Google WorkspaceUK IT and security teams face mounting pressure from legacy technology By Justin Anderson Nov 13, 2024 GmailNew summary cards in Gmail help track purchases, events and more By Maria Fernandez Guajardo Oct 02, 2024 GmailHow to use Gemini in Gmail to manage your inbox like a pro By Maria Fernandez Guajardo Sep 12, 2024 Google Workspace5 tips for writing great prompts for Gemini in the Workspace side panel By Molly McHugh-Johnson Jul 29, 2024 Learning \u0026 EducationNew AI tools for Google Workspace for Education By Akshay Kirtikar \u0026 Brian Hendricks Jun 24, 2024 .",
